5 September 2017

The 8th Century BC

  • Colonization
    • Corcyra, settled by Corinthians, c.734 BC
    • Syracuse, settled by Corinthians, c.734 BC
    • Cumae, settled by Chalcidians, before 725 BC
  • Panhellenic Games
    • First Olympic games 776 BC, led to Olympiad dating system. 2017/8 = 1st year of the 699th Olympiad.
    • Pythian Games at Delphi; music and athletic competitions; every 8 years at first, after 585 BC held 3rd year of each Olympiad
    • Nemean and Isthmian games held in 2nd and 4th years of each Olympiad from the c6 onward

Writing

  • Linear B (extinct c.1100 BC) –> Cypriot Syllabary (extince c.300 BC)
    • Syllabic (consonant & vowel)
  • Phoenecian
    • Abjad (consonants only, no vowels)
    • Derived from Egyptian heiroglyphs
    • Evolved into Greek, Latin, Hebrew, Syriac, Arabic, and other scripts

Neck of the "Nessos Amphora," Athens, 625-600 BC, National Archaeological Museum

The "Cup of Nestor" From Pithekoussai, c. 750-700 BC. Cf Iliad, 11.632-637.

[I am] Nestor's cup, good to drink from. // Whoever drinks from this cup, him straightaway // the desire of beautiful-crowned Aphrodite will seize.

Homer

'Homer Caetani', Roman copy (C2 AD?) of Hellenistic statue

A real person?

  • Poems date to second half C8: Iliad c.750, Odyssey c. 725 BC.
  • Ancients attributed both to the same poet, Homer
  • Chios and Smyrna (Asia Minor) have best claim to be his birthplace
  • Debate about unity of poems C18 - early C20, put to rest by better understanding of oral poetry composition
  • Poems have "fossilized" memory of Mycenean past (ended c.1200 BC), supported by archaeology; reflect Dark Age society

Oral Poetry, Written Poem

  • Division into 24 books more recent
  • Milman Parry & Oral poetry in C20 Yugoslavia
    • Illiteracy
    • Dactylic ( u u - ) Hexameter (7)
    • Mixed dialect (mostly Ionic with Aeolic; some very archaic forms)
    • Pervasive repetition
    • Traditional phrases (formulae)
    • Repetitive but flexible patterns in the story ("themes"), e.g. arming, arriving/departing, sacrifices, fighting scenes
  • Written down? Memorized by Homeridae & Rhapsodes? Written text in Athens in C6

Iliad 18 & Ekphrasis

  • Ekphrasis: "Extended and detailed lieterary description of any object, real or imaginary."
    • Valuable for art history
    • Literary genre, sometimes used as rhetorical exercise
    • e.g. Lucian, Eikones (C2 AD); Philostratus of Lemnos, Eikones (early C3 AD); Callistratus, Ekphraseis (C3 or 4 AD)

From 1720 edition of Pope's translation of the Iliad

Gods and War: Iliad 18.516-9.

… And Ares led them, and Pallas Athene. // These were gold, both, and golden raiment upon them, and they were // beautiful and huge in their armour, being divinities, // and conspicuous from afar, but the people around them were smaller.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)

Agriculture and sacrifice: Iliad 18.558-60.

And apart and under a tree the heralds made a feast ready // and trimmed a great ox they had slaughtered. Meanwhile the women // scattered, for the wormken to eat, abundant white barley.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)

Performance: Iliad 18.569-72.

And in their midst a youth with a singing lyre played charmingly // upon it for them, and sang the beautiful song for Linos // in a light voice, and they followed him, and with singing and whistling // and light dance-steps of their feet kept time to the music.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)

Vivid details: Iliad 18.535-8; 18.582-4.

And Hate was there with Confusion among the, and Death the destructive; // she was holding a live man with a new wound, and another // one unhurt, and dragged a dead man by the feet through the carnage. // The clothing upon her shoulders showed strong red with the men's blood.

But the two lions, breaking open th hide of the great ox, // gulped the black blood and the inward guts, as meanwhile herdsmen // were in the act of setting and urging the quick dogs on them.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)

Mythological References: Iliad 18.590-2.

And the renowned smith of the strong arms made elaborate on it // a dancing floor, like that which once in the wide spaces of Knossos // Daidalos built for Ariadne of the lovely tresses.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)

Geography: Iliad 18.606-7.

He made on it the great strength of the Ocean River // which ran around the utmost rim of the shield's strong structure.

Tr. Lattimore (1951)
